<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO CLASS LASS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Oct 12 17:40:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Class Lass,<br><br>
AH! HA! You caught me stuck in one of those time warp loops that still reside in my mind, and are triggered by whatever floats by that satisfies the need. Time ceases in that place. The real time of me, the here and present, gets lost.<br><br>
Combat mode it is. As I read my posts back one or two, It is clear that I was feeling things out to determine your place and your motive in the scheme of things. Your lengthy post has clarified some of those issues, and I am starting on my way down to the here and now. It will take a little while, some contemplation, some relaxation exercises, and  reconnection. <br><br>
My crash last weekend and a few other things triggered it and started the process. <br><br>
To answer your question:<br><br>
&quot;What do you mean by &quot;that which was lost&quot;?&quot;,<br><br>
I feel that the Vietnam Vortex, as I have called it in the past for the lack of a better descriptive phrase for the event in total, drew from many 'NamVets their self-esteem, their pride, emotions, and other psychological attributes, and in many cases, through survival dissociative processes, themselves.<br><br>
Historically, and even back several thousand years, societies have had some mechanism to heal and reverse the effects of combat to re-integrate the veteran into society in a meaningfull way. It is the obligation of society to do that because society put the veteran into the combat situation in the first place. <br><br>
In the specific context of the Vietnam Veteran, there was nothing when the umbilical was severed in Oakland, or wherever. When I walked through those doors, it was the beginning of a journey unlike that experienced by my father and grandfather in other conflicts. It was as if I had been beamed over to a leper colony on a remote island in another country.<br><br>
These are my feelings about that which was lost. While I cherish the Welcome Home! from my fellow Vets, there is an emptiness that remains.<br><br>
Art   
